	keywords = {data, work, future of work, labor, weather stations},
	annote = {Ghost work is any work that can be at least partially sourced (finding the person to do the work), scheduled, managed, shipped, and billed through some combination of an application programming interface (or API), the internet, and artificial intelligence. It is really a phrase meant to conceptualize work conditions that erase the value of people in a highly constrained workflow mediated by digital technologies. There are plenty of examples of on-demand labor or information service work that are organized through this process of bringing in application programming interfaces, the internet, and AI. Unless a person, company, or end consumer is valuing the person who is contributing to the production of information or services in that moment, it can quickly slide into ghost work conditions. Systems that depend on data to map out decision trees for computational processes rely on people to label the training data—fixing typos and broken hyperlinks, adding descriptive tags, removing accidental characters, etc. People make this data legible to software. Computer scientists developing algorithms need people to improve the “guesses” that AI makes about things, such as whether an image is a dog or cat or whether an email is spam. And, increasingly, people are hired to plug into the workflow of automated systems that can't be trusted to make decisions or answer questions as well as humans do. That's who “ghost workers” are; they are the people filling in the gaps and making emerging digital technologies work.},
}

