	annote = {Study conducted by embedded researchers on the founding of SSA. 10/1935-3/1937 Recognized the SS old age pension is an annuity. SSA of 1935: old age pensions; state-administered, federally supervised unemployment insurance; progam of subsidies to the states for aid to needy. Slow start b/c Long filibuster prevented appropriations needed to fund SSA for several months. UI: State plans must have (1) benefits paid through state employment office of other agency approved by SSB; (2) no benefits until 2 yrs after first contributions; (3) state fund monies depositied in Treasury, ear-marked trust fund. SSA wants to contol state UI offices and policies. Hard to do. limited success in study period. Social Security: Must begin collecting payroll taxes on 1 Jan 1937 No monthly benefits paid out until 1942. BUT: anyone reaching 65 after 1/1/37 and before 1/1/42 is eligible for a lump sum payment of 3.5\% of wages since 12/31/36 up until 65th birthday “Payroll taxes had been adopted despite their regressive tendencies. The issue was, in the President's words `politics all the way through.' `We put payroll contributions there,' he said, `so as to give the contributors a legal, moral, and political right to collect their pensions and their unemployment benefits. With those taxes there is no damn politician can ever scrap my social security program.‴ [17; quoted from Leuchtenburg, Roosevelt and the New Deal, p. 133] Foreign consultants: concern about separation of tax collecting (Treasury) and info-collecting (SSA) functions. States seeking help in drafting UI bills and designing systems. SSA overwhelmed in 1936. Major problem was lack of professionalism in many state bureaucracies. The roll out of old age pensions: Struggle to staff the old age pensions section. Need to ramp up quickly. civil service rules were a concern but were ultimately respected (probably due to slack labor market). Confirming workers' ages was not an easy thing. Census was expected to help. director of old age benefits was absorbed with duties relating to railroad workers. Decided that SSA would have to do registration itself. Big fight over what SSNs would be and look like. Intersting problems with early computing and whether there should be alphanumeric SSNs. Fight over what info to collect. Decided to collect race info (word used is “color”) b/c of differences in life expectancies. Some argued for asking about religion since “many employers specified that members of certain faiths were unacceptable. The Employment Service took the position that it was better to send an employer people he wanted rather than to let an employee begin a job and then be fired because if religious prejudice.” (326) Questions of whether to collection union affiliation. Fight over term to use for registration. Official term ends up as “assignment of account numbers.” 1936 election had huge effect on timing of SS registration. Strong pressure to wait until after the presidential election to start sending out forms and enrolling employers and workers. Lots of hemming and hawing on timing. On purely administrative basis, get started sooner; waiting until after 1/1/37 would cause huge tax headaches for employers. Finally decided in 6/36 to start registration after the election. SSA would do the registration work. Employer opinion solicited. Post Office was ultimately key in roll out of registration process. Required Presidential pressure to get USPS to buy in fully, 9/15/36. Postmen recorded the employers on their routes. Employer census from postal workers ultimately destroyed before being turned over to IRS/Treasury (serious fuck up) SSA kept a low profile and did not enage in serious publicity or other actions to raise public awareness or advocate for registration until Landon campaign (9/26/36) and republicans began stuffing workers' payroll envelopes with anti-SS propaganda. But once campaign started then SSA division of information services swung into action. Newsreels; interviews. SSB vigorously cooperated with Democratic party and labor in the weeks before the election. Released We the People and Social Security newsreel [NEED TO FIND THIS.] Released “Security in Your Old Age” 9pp. pamphlet [NEED TO FIND THIS] “The first paragraph of this circular was changed, because social security had become and issue in the election, to read:`There is now a law in this country which will give about 26 million working people something to live on when they are old and have stopped working. This law, which gives other benefits too, was passed last year by Congress and is called the Social Security Act.‴(358) “One evening 125 members of the Social Security Board staff, including some executives, stuffed 33,000 envelopes with 100 copies each of this circular to be sent to 33,000 local AFL unions throughout the country, following upon a letter sent out by William Green, president of the national AFL” (358) Republican attack a “blessing in diguise because it awakened the American public to the fact that there was a Social Security Act, and because it made it possible to run a quick and effective publicity campaign.” (359) tons of last minute timing changes and questions; personality fights about titles and who has control over regional directors and field office managers. Treasury sent out a different tax form to employers about UI insurance at same time as SS-4 (employer) tax form went out, so some confusion. Between 11/16/26 and 2/15/37 there were 23647000 received appications for SSNs. This study not able to really judge quality of roll out. But seems like post office did a reasonable job. Serious problems with roll out of interim, lump-sum benefits. Method and forms for confirming benefit eligibility were onerous and complicated and largely not worth the effort. Field offices had strong concerns that there would be serious backlash. Caused problems but ultimately no coverage or backlash. },
