roups. 1) as the proportion of non-rich increases (holding ethnic divisions fixed) it is more difficult for class parties to win. As ethnic polarization increases (size of majority group's majority decreases) it is easier for ethnic party to win 2) when ethnic politics prevails rich and poor split their votes; when class politics prevails rich vote together and poor vote together. aka: as inequality increases (holding ethnic polarization fixed) there should be weaker relationship between vote choice and income. 3) When ethnic politics prevails then less rich-to-poor redistribution. Contrasts with antipathy approach in which level of inequality should have no effect on redistribution. 4) When ethnic polarization is high then democracy is less expensive for autocratic elites so transitions are easier. Chapter 6: a justification of the EITM approach vs. causal ID-driven research. Basic answer: ID-driven reseaerch prevents us from asking certain kinds of questions, esp those about social structure and broad macro stuff. Also hard in interpret in an eqbm framework. External validity questions. chapters 7-9: a whole set of X-national regressions on: support for redistribution; level of redistribution; ethnification of political parties; democratic transitions. Basically testing interaction terms. Plenty of opportunity to replicate the stuff in the 2nd 1/2 of the book.},
